704. Binary Search
Problem

Given a sorted array nums in ascending order and a target value, return its index if found; otherwise return -1.

Constraint: The algorithm must run in O(log n) time.

Key Observation

The array is already sorted.

Instead of checking every element one by one, we can repeatedly divide the search space into two halves and eliminate the half that cannot contain the target.

This approach is called Binary Search.

Why Not Linear Search?
Linear Search
for(int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    if(nums[i] == target)
        return i;
}
return -1;
Complexity
Time: O(n)
Space: O(1)

Although this returns the correct answer, it does not satisfy the required O(log n) complexity.

Binary Search Idea
Find the middle element.
If middle element equals target → return index.
If target is greater than middle element → search right half.
If target is smaller than middle element → search left half.
Repeat until target is found or search space becomes empty.
Dry Run
nums = [-1,0,3,5,9,12]
target = 9
Step 1
low = 0
high = 5

mid = (0 + 5) / 2 = 2

nums[mid] = 3

Since:

9 > 3

Search right half.

low = mid + 1 = 3
Step 2
low = 3
high = 5

mid = (3 + 5) / 2 = 4

nums[mid] = 9

Target found.

return 4
Binary Search Template
int low = 0;
int high = nums.length - 1;

while(low <= high) {
    int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

    if(nums[mid] == target)
        return mid;

    else if(nums[mid] < target)
        low = mid + 1;

    else
        high = mid - 1;
}

return -1;
Why Use low + (high - low) / 2?

Instead of:

int mid = (low + high) / 2;

we use:

int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

to avoid integer overflow when low and high are very large.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity

At each step, half of the search space is discarded.

n → n/2 → n/4 → n/8 → ...

Number of divisions:

log₂(n)

Therefore:

Time Complexity = O(log n)
Space Complexity

Only a few variables are used.

Space Complexity = O(1)
Important Conditions for Binary Search

✅ Array must be sorted.

✅ Search space should be reducible by half each iteration.

✅ Use while(low <= high) for standard binary search.

Common Mistakes
Mistake 1
while(low < high)

May skip checking the last remaining element.

Use:

while(low <= high)
Mistake 2
low = mid;

Can cause an infinite loop.

Use:

low = mid + 1;
Mistake 3
high = mid;

Can cause an infinite loop.

Use:

high = mid - 1;
Pattern Recognition

Use Binary Search when:

Array is sorted.
Searching for an element.
Finding first/last occurrence.
Finding lower bound or upper bound.
Finding minimum/maximum in a sorted structure.
Problem asks for O(log n) complexity.

Core Idea:
"Whenever a sorted structure allows us to eliminate half of the search space in each step, Binary Search is a potential solution."
